vement, the organizing of undocumented workers, and the Chicano Renaissance.  Weaving this revolution against a backdrop of historic Mexican American activism from the 1930s to the 1960s and the contemporary black power and black civil rights movements, García gives readers the best representations of the Chicano generation in Los Angeles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChicano movementzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a1960s los angeles.  a1968 la school.  a1970s los angeles.  ablack berets.  acesar chavez.  achicano antiwar movement.  achicano family.  achicano farmworkers.  achicano feminism.  achicano history.  achicano lit.  achicano movement.  achicano studies.  acivil rights movement.  aethnic studies.  agloria arellanes.  ahispanic american studies.  ala raza unida.  alatin american studies.  amexican american activism.  amexican american history.  amexican american lit.  araul ruiz.  arosalio munoz.  asouthwest us history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028601640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096136440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961364/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY